 ({{percentage|65,794,399|136,669,276|2}})\n|45 ({{percentage|45|100}}){{refn|Additionally, the two [[independent politician|independent]] Senators both caucus with the Democratic Party.<ref name=\"U.S. Senate: Party Division\" />|group=upper-alpha|name=b}}\n|235 ({{percentage|235|435}}){{refn|Additionally, four of the six [[non-voting members of the United States House of Representatives]] caucus with the Democratic Party.<ref name=\"Directory of Representatives\" />|group=upper-alpha|name=c}}\n|3,446 ({{percentage|3,446|7,383}})\n|18 ({{percentage|18|50}})\n|24 ({{percentage|24|50}})\n|14 ({{percentage|14|49}})\n|-\n|}\n\n=== Third parties ===\n{{More citations needed|section|date=May 2019}}\n==== Elected in state legislatures or congress ====\n{| class=\"plainrowheaders sortable wikitable\"\n|- \"\n! scope=\"col\" |Party\n! scope=\"col\" |Ideology\n! scope=\"col\" |Founded\n! scope=\"col\" data-sort-type=\"number\" |Presidential vote (2016)<br /><ref name=\"Minor parties\">{{Cite web|url=https://transition.fec.gov/pubrec/fe2016/2016presgeresults.pdf|title=Official 2016 Presidential General Election Results|date=January 30, 2018|website=Federal Election Commission|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170818141559/https://transition.fec.gov/pubrec/fe2016/2016presgeresults.pdf|archive-date=August 18, 2017|access-date=November 3, 2018|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n! scope=\"col\" |State Legislators\n|-\n|[[Vermont Progressive Party]]\n|[[Progressivism]] {{cn|date=December 2019}}\n|1981\n|0\n|9 ({{percentage|9|7,383|2}})\n|-\n|[[Independence Party of New York]]\n|[[Populism]] {{cn|date=December 2019}}\n|1991\n|0\n|1 ({{Percentage|1|7383|2}})\n|}\n\n==== Not elected in state legislatures or congress ====\n\n{| class=\"plainrowheaders sortable wikitable\"\n|- \"\n! scope=\"col\" |Party\n! scope=\"col\" |Ideology\n! scope=\"col\" |Founded\n! scope=\"col\" data-sort-type=\"number\" |Presidential vote (2016)<br /><ref name=\"Minor parties\">{{Cite web|url=https: